  "prompt": "How can iron form 5 bonds in Fe(CO)5?",
  "response": "In Fe(CO)5, iron forms 5 bonds to carbon monoxide (CO) molecules through a unique bonding mechanism:\n\n1. Electronic Configuration:\n- Iron is in the zero oxidation state\n- It uses its 3d and 4s orbitals for bonding\n\n2. Bonding Mechanism:\n- CO molecules act as ligands\n- Carbon of CO donates a lone pair of electrons to the metal\n- Simultaneously, empty \u03c0* antibonding orbitals of CO accept electron density back from iron (\u03c0-backbonding)\n\n3. Orbital Overlap:\n- 4s and 3d orbitals of iron hybridize\n- This allows formation of 5 equivalent bonds\n- Results in a trigonal bipyramidal molecular geometry\n\n4. Electron Counting:\n- Each CO contributes 2 electrons to the metal\n- 5 CO ligands provide 10 electrons\n- These electrons fill the iron's valence shell, achieving 18-electron configuration\n\n5. Stability:\n- \u03c0-backbonding strengthens the Fe-C bonds\n- Electron sharing makes the complex very stable\n\nThis synergistic bonding between iron and CO enables the formation of 5 bonds in Fe(CO)5.",
